{"pageProps":{"tutorial":{"title":"CSS Icons","slug":"css-icons","subject":"CSS","category":"Web Development","level":"Beginner","estimated_read_time":"8 mins","prerequisites":["CSS Fonts"],"learning_objectives":["Understand how to use icon libraries","Learn about Font Awesome","Learn about Google Material Icons","Style icons using CSS"],"theory":"The simplest way to add icons to your HTML page is with an icon library, such as Font Awesome, Bootstrap Icons, or Google Icons.\n\nSince these icons are essentially vectors or fonts, you can customize them with CSS (size, color, shadow, etc.) just like text.","syntax":"<!-- Import -->\n<link rel=\"stylesheet\" href=\"https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/font-awesome/4.7.0/css/font-awesome.min.css\">\n\n<!-- Usage -->\n<i class=\"fa fa-cloud\"></i>","examples":[{"code":"<i class=\"fa fa-car\" style=\"font-size:48px;color:red;\"></i>","output":"Displays a large red car icon.","explanation":"Icons scale without losing quality because they are vectors."}],"common_mistakes":[{"mistake":"Using image tags for simple icons","correction":"Use icon fonts or SVGs for scalability and performance.","example":"WRONG: <img src='icon.png'>\nCORRECT: <i class='fa fa-user'></i>"}],"interview_questions":[{"question":"Why are icon fonts/SVGs better than raster images?","answer":"They are scalable (no blurriness on zoom), smaller in file size, and can be styled with CSS color/size properties.","difficulty":"Easy"}],"practice_problems":[{"problem":"Include the Google Material Icons library.","hint":"Use a link tag pointing to Google Fonts API.","solution":"<link rel=\"stylesheet\" href=\"https://fonts.googleapis.com/icon?family=Material+Icons\">","difficulty":"Easy"}],"real_world_use_cases":[{"scenario":"Action Buttons","description":"User interfaces rely on icons (Trash can for delete, Pencil for edit) to save space and convey meaning quickly.","code":"<button><i class=\"fa fa-trash\"></i> Delete</button>"}],"exam_notes":["Most icon librari